            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the North Carolina income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                North Carolina uses a
                <strong>flat state income tax rate</strong>. That means your
                taxable income is taxed at the same percentage, regardless of
                how high or low your income is. The calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Applies the correct <strong>NC standard deduction</strong> for
                  your filing status and year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts any <strong>pre-tax deductions</strong> you enter
                  (401(k), HSA, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Computes your <strong>NC taxable income</strong> and
                  multiplies it by the flat rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally estimates your
                  <strong>federal income tax</strong> using current brackets and
                  the federal standard deduction.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Shows your <strong>effective NC tax rate</strong> and
                  <strong>take-home pay</strong> annually and per pay period.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>
                Current North Carolina income tax rate and standard deduction
              </h3>
              <p>For recent tax years, North Carolina has:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  A <strong>flat state income tax rate</strong> (same for all
                  brackets).
                </li>
                <li>
                  A <strong>standard deduction</strong> that depends on filing
                  status.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator is preloaded with typical values for 2023 and
                2024. Always confirm the latest numbers with the NC Department
                of Revenue.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">NC taxable income formula</p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >NC taxable income = max( 0, Gross income − Pre-tax
                    deductions − NC standard deduction − Extra NC itemized
                    deductions )</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">NC state income tax</p>
                <p>
                  <code>NC tax = NC taxable income × NC flat tax rate</code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step-by-step example</h3>
              <p>Suppose you are single in 2024 with:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Gross income: <strong>$60,000</strong></li>
                <li>Pre-tax deductions: <strong>$3,000</strong> (401(k))</li>
                <li>No additional NC itemized deductions</li>
              </ul>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Adjusted income after pre-tax:
                  <code>$60,000 − $3,000 = $57,000</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract NC standard deduction (single):
                  <code>$57,000 − standard deduction</code>
                </li>
                <li>Result is your <strong>NC taxable income</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Multiply by the NC flat rate to get your
                  <strong>NC state tax</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>
                Frequently asked questions about North Carolina income tax
              </h2>

              <h3>Who has to file a North Carolina income tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                In general, you must file an NC individual income tax return if
                you are a resident or part‑year resident and your income exceeds
                the state filing threshold for your filing status. Nonresidents
                must file if they have NC‑source income above the threshold.
                Exact thresholds change over time, so check the latest
                instructions on the NC Department of Revenue website.
              </p>

              <h3>Does North Carolina tax Social Security benefits?</h3>
              <p>
                North Carolina
                <strong>does not tax Social Security benefits</strong>. However,
                other retirement income (pensions, IRA distributions, 401(k)
                withdrawals) is generally taxable at the flat NC rate unless a
                specific exclusion applies.
              </p>

              <h3>Are there local income taxes in North Carolina?</h3>
              <p>
                No. North Carolina has a
                <strong>state-level income tax only</strong>. Cities and
                counties do not levy their own local income taxes, although they
                may impose sales and property taxes.
              </p>

              <h3>How does this calculator differ from official NC tools?</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed for
                <strong>quick planning</strong> and shows both NC and federal
                estimates in one view. It does not handle every credit,
